When we read contemporary literature, how do we know what is valuable, good or lasting?  Do we immediately recognise a "classic" work by its scope, complexity and challenge or its daring, beauty or dissidence?  How and why does the "classic" text emerge in the present?  Though "contemporary classic" sounds like a pitch used by publishers, is this a term that might enable discussion of rich and compelling literary works from the last thirty years?

The course answers this question by moving beyond the dominant tropes of the British Raj, replete with civilising missions, bejewelled maharajas and tiger hunts, to present a critical interrogation of colonial dynamics, demonstrating the relationships between imperial oppression, anti-colonial violence and Gandhian nonviolence, which culminated in the independence of India and the creation of East and West Pakistan, in 1947.

ARTS3638.desc: Given the popularity of both Japanese comics or manga and anime with learners of Japanese, the course focuses on a single title (available both in manga and anime) that reflects various aspects of contemporary Japanese life such as family life, education, and work.

ARTS3639.desc: By using the broad social themes of post-1945 Japanese politics, economics and cultural development, this course attempts to produce an alternative socio-cultural timeline by considering how these themes were and are represented in domestic Japanese popular culture.

ARTS3640.course_name: Japan and Korea: Cultures in Conflict
ARTS3640.desc: Focuses on the relations between Japan and Korea from the late 19th century and the role of Japanese colonialism in the development of Korean cultural nationalism.

ARTS3641.desc: This course provides you with an opportunity to learn how to interact successfully when working and doing business with Japanese people.

ARTS3643.desc: This course presents an opportunity for you to develop reading and writing skills in Japanese with a wide variety of text genres.

ARTS3660.desc: This Course provides an Advanced level program in Korean language study from a communicative and task-based approach.

ARTS3661.desc: This course continues to provide Advanced level tuition in Korean language study from a communicative and task-based approach.

ARTS3662.desc: The course explores language use and underlying cultural values in contemporary Korea, using selected Korean dramas, films, songs and TV talk shows.

ARTS3663.desc: This course provides a professional and business Korean program from thematic and task-based approaches.

ARTS3664.desc: This course provides a para-professional level translation program in Korean from a task-based approach.

ARTS3665.desc: This course provides a para-professional level interpreting program in Korean from a task-based approach.

ARTS3667.course_name: Teaching Korean as a Foreign Language
ARTS3667.desc: Explores issues relating to teaching Korean as a Foreign Language.

ARTS3690.desc: This course will enable you to develop skills in extracting and synthesising information regarding linguistic diversity.

ARTS3695.desc: In this course you will learn about the factors which impact on the spread and use of various languages and you will develop an understanding of how policies and language planning initiatives can change the language ecology of multicultural and multilingual communities.

ARTS3750.desc: Are you interested in understanding and tackling important environment-development challenges in the 21st century? Do you think a community-based approach to development and environment management delivers more sustainable and equitable outcomes? The course interrogates these and many more critical questions surrounding the community-based approach to development and environmental management.

ARTS3751.course_name: Development Studies: Research, Practice and Ethics
ARTS3751.desc: How is development theory translated into practical outcomes? How can we make sure that a good idea leads to good development programmes and projects? This course provides you with a cutting-edge for entering into development practice as it exposes you to the real-life challenges you will face when working in development organisations.

ARTS3755.desc: In this course, you will draw upon the knowledge and skills from previous courses to design a humanitarian or development project.

ARTS3756.desc: In Current Debates in Development Studies we will analyse the concepts and cases at the heart of current debates in Development Studies from the global to the local level (and back again).

ARTS3757.course_name: Experiences and Everyday Practices of Development
ARTS3757.desc: The anthropology of development and critical development studies have been central to understanding the everyday experiences and unintended consequences of development.

ARTS3758.desc: This course provides you with the unique opportunity to gain international exposure and deeper understanding of the political, social and cultural context of a development context.

ARTS3759.course_name: Preparing for and Reflecting on International Internships
ARTS3759.desc: This course prepares you for the intensive demands of an international work-integrated learning experience.

ARTS3780.desc: Germany has faced enormous challenges and undergone radical transformations since the end of the Second World War, when it was a defeated, occupied pariah with no central government.

ARTS3783.course_name: Great, Emerging and Declining Powers in the Contemporary World
ARTS3783.desc: ARTS3783 examines the foreign policies of a number of the world's major powers from 1945 to the present.

ARTS3786.course_name: Confronting the Past in Contemporary Europe
ARTS3786.desc: What role does Europe's terrible twentieth-century history play today and how has this changed since 1945? To what extent does history divide or unite Europeans? Has Germany 'come to terms' with its Nazi past? How are Stalinism and the Soviet Union remembered in Putin's Russia? In this course you will explore how Europeans have coped with their recent pasts, particularly the experiences of fascism and Nazism, of World War II and the Holocaust, and of Soviet-style communism.

ARTS3787.desc: Whether in public or academic discourse the notions of modernity and modern are ubiquitous.

ARTS3789.course_name: Ethnic and Religious Minorities in Modern Europe
ARTS3789.desc: This course examines interethnic and interfaith relations in Europe in the last two centuries.

ARTS3810.course_name: Politics & International Relations: Theory and Practice
ARTS3810.desc: What is theory? What is praxis? What assumptions guide us when we theorise about events or phenomena in domestic and global politics? And what does it mean to undertake theoretically informed research and then actually apply it, in the discipline of Politics & International Relations? This course encourages you to consider the broader context of the discipline through critical, reflective and engaged thinking about contemporary Pols & IR.

ARTS3812.course_name: Manias, Panics and Crashes: Global Political Economy in an Era of Crisis
ARTS3812.desc: The period from the early 1970s is often noted as a particularly volatile one for the global political economy (GPE).

ARTS3814.desc: This course introduces you to the theory and practice of Australian foreign policy across a range of key relationships and policy areas in both historical and contemporary terms.

ARTS3816.desc: Considers the nature of US engagement with international law during the years of its rise to superpower status and since, and the impact of the US on international law.

ARTS3817.course_name: The Middle East and International Law
ARTS3817.desc: This course will encourage you to examine the way in which international law and the Middle East interact.

ARTS3819.desc: What do we mean by the 'new' security agenda? Are emerging threats to international security really 'new'? If so, how should security studies scholars analyse them, and what are the implications for security praxis? How are policymakers dealing with these emerging or 'new' security challenges, to what effect, and what are some of the alternatives? These are some of the key questions explored in this course, which investigates the broad and evolving agenda of security studies, and key themes and dynamics in contemporary security relations.

ARTS3820.course_name: How to start a revolution: activism, social movements and political change
ARTS3820.desc: How to start a revolution and change the world? In a world of growing inequality, environmental pollution, and conflict this question seems more important than ever.

ARTS3821.course_name: The Politics of Identity in the 21st Century
ARTS3821.desc: Encompassing a variety of timely, globally relevant topics, reflected through various identity lenses, including those of gender, race, class, culture, and sexuality the course interrogates the intersection of identities, politics, and public policy.

ARTS3822.desc: The systematic study of politics has a long history, stretching back some two and a half thousand years to the ancient Greeks.

ARTS3850.course_name: Security in Asia: Politics Meets Economics
ARTS3850.desc: In this course you will examine the complex and dynamic relationship between political and economic processes and outcomes in Asia.

ARTS3870.course_name: Debates and Controversies in Sociology and Anthropology
ARTS3870.desc: This capstone course gives you an opportunity to reflect upon key recent and classical debates in sociology and anthropology, drawing on a range of contemporary social problems as critical case studies.

ARTS3871.desc: In this course you will be confronted with fascinating riddles.

ARTS3872.desc: In this course, you will explore broad sociological and anthropological understandings of media and theories of power and knowledge that exist in the public sphere and social life.

ARTS3874.desc: This course explores the rise of human rights discourse and its relationship to other discourses on suffering and social justice.

ARTS3875.desc: In this course you will reflect on the practice of key social research methods for investigating culture and society.

ARTS3883.desc: How do individuals experience the process of growing older? Considering a range of Asian societies, this course examines how the biological language of ageing relates to the cultural language of maturation, youth, adulthood, and old age.

ARTS3885.desc: The concept of trauma has become increasingly central to individual and collective negotiations with the darker realities of our past and present, including interpersonal and civic violence and the legacies of colonisation and genocide.

ARTS3886.course_name: Living Social Justice: Experience and Practice
ARTS3886.desc: In this course, you will explore the relationship between justice, social life and everyday experience.

ARTS3900.course_name: Gender and Queer Critiques: Rethinking History and Other Studies
ARTS3900.desc: This seminar course acts as a Capstone for students in the WGS minor.

ARTS3901.desc: We often understand knowledge as a neutral, disinterested point of view: as purely rational, untainted by partiality or prejudice, and detached from the social and political entanglements that cloud objectivity.

ARTS3991.desc: The Arts & Social Sciences Capstone is a multi-disciplinary course that provides you with an opportunity to reflect on your disciplinary studies over the previous three levels of study.

ARTS4100.desc: This Honours-level seminar course is designed to introduce students to higher-level academic research and writing in the disciplines of English, Film, Media, Music, Theatre, Dance and Performance Studies.

ARTS4202.desc: Note: This is a 12 UOC course.

ARTS4247.desc: This course will help you to develop a range of higher-level research skills.

ARTS4249.desc: Note: This is a 12 UOC course.

ARTS4266.course_name: Puzzles, Planning, and Presentation for Honours in the Social Sciences
ARTS4266.desc: This is a compulsory course for Social Sciences honours students in the School of Social Sciences.

ARTS4268.desc: Note: This is a 12 UOC course.

ATSI0001.desc: Enabling Skills 1 introduces students to fundamental skills of studying at university.

ATSI0002.desc: Enabling Skills 2 develops the fundamental skills of studying at university.

ATSI1011.desc: Indigenous Australia is the gateway course to the Indigenous Studies Major.

ATSI1012.desc: In this course students are introduced to Aboriginal Sydney through local written and oral histories, as well as notable works in film, performance, television and art, seeking to make visible Aboriginal experiences, lives and connections to place in the city.

ATSI2003.course_name: Indigenous Material Culture-Objects and Their Journey
ATSI2003.desc: The focus of this course is on the role of museums and art galleries in the representation of Indigenous peoples and their cultures.

ATSI2004.desc: Representations and misrepresentations of Australian Indigeneity as part of the national identity are most often portrayed through forms of popular culture.

ATSI2011.desc: Indigenous Australian Political History tells the story of Indigenous resistance, activism and political organisation during the twentieth century in Australia.

ATSI2012.desc: Contemporary Issues in Indigenous Politics examines contemporary debates in Australian Indigenous affairs, placing an emphasis on the political contexts within which these debates take place.

ATSI2014.desc: This course aims to develop student understanding of the role of public policy in shaping Indigenous communities.

ATSI2015.desc: In this course students will explore the history, philosophy, theory, and methods of Western science and ethnoscience.

ATSI3002.desc: The course explores the way in which gender influences and structures the experiences of Indigenous women and men in the past and the present.

ATSI3003.course_name: Indigenous Cultural Heritage and the Environment
ATSI3003.desc: This course explores Indigenous perspectives on the management of country, waterways, culture and heritage in Australia.

ATSI3005.desc: There are (at least) two sides to the colonial relationship.

ATSI3008.desc: This is the Capstone course for students completing the Indigenous Studies Major.

ATSI4001.course_name: Advanced Indigenous Studies: Issues and Debates

ATSI7002.desc: The Indigenous Pre-Law course is an intensive four-week residential course for prospective Indigenous students wanting to enrol in an undergraduate degree in Law at UNSW.

ATSI7003.desc: The PMP is an intensive academic program that runs for four weeks at the University of New South Wales in Sydney.

ATSI7004.desc: The Indigenous Pre-Social Work course is designed for Indigenous students wanting to enter the Bachelor of Social Work or any of the combined Social Work degrees.

ATSI7006.desc: The Pre-Teacher Education Program is an academic preparatory and enabling program designed for Indigenous students to undertake further undergraduate degree studies in education for the pupose of becoming secondary school teachers.

ATSI7007.desc: The Indigenous Pre-Science/Engineering course is an intensive four-week residential course for prospective Indigenous students wanting to enrol in an undergraduate degree in the faculties of Science or Engineering at UNSW.

AVEN1920.desc: This course gives an explanation of how aircraft fly and how engineering technologies relate to the vehicle.

AVIA1111.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for Recreational Pilot Licence level Basic Aeronautical Knowledge, specifically the BAKC, RBKA, RFRC, RMTC and PHFC units of competency.

AVIA1321.desc: The course provides a foundation for the range of courses provided in the BAv, and includes a general description of the aviation industry.

AVIA1401.desc: Human performance is highly dependent on a number of factors, some of which are under our direct control while others are outside our sphere of control.

AVIA1901.desc: This course covers the economics of an airline and how airline management personnel address airline economic problems.

AVIA1902.course_name: Airline Financial Analysis and Decision Support
AVIA1902.desc: This course is designed to provide students with an understanding of the financial decision-making required in the commercial air transport industry.

AVIA2013.desc: The course comprises the aeronautical theory and associated ground training for Stage 1 of the Bachelor of Aviation (Flying).

AVIA2014.desc: Pre-requisites: AVIA1002 or 2013Excluded: AVIA2003, AVIA2004The course comprises the aeronautical theory and associated ground training for Stage 2 of the Bachelor of Aviation (Flying).

AVIA2025.desc: Airborne drones (unmanned aerial vehicles (or remotely piloted aircraft (RPA)) of varying shapes and sizes are permeating the civil aviation sector across recreational, commercial and research activities.

AVIA2101.course_name: Baggage Handling System Design, Technology & Operations
AVIA2101.desc: A good working baggage handling system is essential for the functioning of modern airports.

AVIA2111.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for commercial pilot licence level Navigation, specifically the PNVC and CNVC units of competency.

AVIA2112.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for commercial pilot licence level meteorology, specifically the PMTC and CMTC units of competency.

AVIA2113.course_name: Commercial Human Factors, Flight Rules and Air Law
AVIA2113.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for commercial pilot licence level Human Factors, Flight Rules and Air Law, specifically, the CHFC, CFRA and CFRC units of competency.

AVIA2114.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for commercial pilot licence level Aircraft General Knowledge (Aeroplane), specifically the PAKC, PAKA (Section 2), CAKC (Sections 2.

AVIA2115.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the Civil Aviation Safety Regulations 1998 Part 61 Manual of Standards for commercial pilot licence level Aerodynamics, specifically the Commerical Aerodynamics - all aircraft categories (CADC) and Commercial Aerodynamics - aeroplane (CADA) units of competency.

AVIA2116.desc: The course includes a component of the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for the grant of a Commercial Pilot Licence specifically POPC, POPA, COPC and COPA units of competency.

AVIA2117.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for the grant of an instrument rating, specifically the IREX and GNSS units of competency.

AVIA2401.desc: This course aims to provide students with an overview of the regulatory structure of civil aviation in Australia.

AVIA2501.desc: This course uses the classic approach to marketing management strategies but is entirely focused on how this is achieved in the airline industry.

AVIA2601.desc: This course aims to introduce students with Operations Research (OR) concepts in the aviation context.

AVIA2701.desc: The first component of this course provides a framework for understanding how airports function, the many demands placed upon them by a wide range of stakeholders and what is needed for airports to be successful at both an operational and business level.

AVIA2801.desc: This course covers the broad range of management decisions faced within the general, corporate and regional aviation sectors and how that is impacted by Government and regulation.

AVIA2910.course_name: Air Transport: Economics and the Environment
AVIA2910.desc: This course is designed to develop non-economics majors economic literacy in the understanding of the key drivers of the commercial air transport industry and the industries impact on society.

AVIA2950.desc: Be up to date with the latest in the aviation industry, both globally and locally.

AVIA3013.desc: The ways in which work can affect people's health, safety and well-being is an important consideration for all organisations.

AVIA3014.desc: The course comprises the aeronautical theory and associated ground training for Stage 3 of the Bachelor of Aviation (Flying).

AVIA3101.desc: This course considers the main facets of corporate airline management, and begins with airline organisational practice, management's visions and objective setting.

AVIA3111.desc: The course includes the aeronautical knowledge training required by the Civil Aviation Safety Regulations 1998 Part 61 Manual of Standards to achieve the competencies of Air Transport Flight Planning, specifically the Air Transport Pilot Flight Planning - Common and Air Transport Pilot Flight Planning - Aeroplane units of competency.

AVIA3112.course_name: Air Transport Aerodynamics and Aircraft Systems
AVIA3112.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for the Air Transport Pilot Licence level Aerodynamics and Aircraft Systems, specifically the AAGC and AAGA units of competency.

AVIA3113.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for the Air Transport Pilot Licence level Navigation and Performance & Loading, specifically the APLC, APLA and ANVC units of competency.

AVIA3114.course_name: Air Transport Air Law, Meteorology and Human Factors
AVIA3114.desc: The course includes all the aeronautical knowledge training required by the CASR 1998 Part 61 MOS for the Air Transport Pilots Licence level Air Law, Meteorology and Human Factors, specifically the AFRC, AFRA, AHFC, AMTC and AMTA units of competency.

AVIA3201.desc: Airline operations are defined as the functional areas which are directly associated with the operations of aircraft or at least in the provision of services for aircraft operations.

AVIA3301.course_name: Simulation Application and Air Traffic Management
AVIA3301.desc: The first component of this course addresses the broad application of simulation to training in the aviation industry.

AVIA3401.desc: The success of safe operations within aviation relies as much on the individual performing his/her role, as on the way he/she interacts with others.

AVIA3410.course_name: Advanced Law and Regulation in Aviation
AVIA3410.desc: The course aims to provide students with a deeper understanding of contemporary aviation law and associated regulations by focusing in greater detail aspects of the course content covered in AVIA2401 by exploring judicial and regulatory developments of both international and domestic case law which is of particular relevance to the contemporary globalized context in which aviation operates.

AVIA3710.desc: Basic research skills are important to the aviation industry.

AVIA3851.desc: This course follows AVIA1850 and provides an in-depth coverage of the key elements outlined in Airport Management 1.

AVIA3900.desc: This course offers an introduction to concepts and tools necessary for understanding the challenges of sustainable development in the transport-environment-tourism nexus.

HUMS1008.course_name: Music on My Mind: Psychology and Music
HUMS1008.desc: This course asks questions about music cognition and behaviour: How do we perceive music? Why can an instrument sound musical? How do we respond to and process the sound? What happens when we are preparing and performing music? Why can performers become debilitatingly nervous? What is the relation between music, sex and cheesecake? Can music make you smarter, and what is the Mozart Effect? Why does that tune get stuck in my head? How old must a person be before they can hear and appreciate music? You will address these and related questions through examination of the music psychology literature, and the critical evaluation of your own musical attitudes, beliefs and behaviours.
